a:71:{s:15:"comment_post_ID";s:4:"9892";s:14:"comment_author";s:10:"Sam Posner";s:20:"comment_author_email";s:16:"samposner@me.com";s:18:"comment_author_url";s:24:"http://nightmaremode.net";s:15:"comment_content";s:1258:"Addendum:
In a previous article, I presented a sort of manifesto of Absurdist game design (http://nightmaremode.net/2011/06/arcade-of-the-absurd-6343/). There, I argued that the main tenant of Absurdism (all ideals and attempts at perfection are ultimately pointless, so one should value the simplicity and reality of life over any quest for completion) can be integrated into video games by counting on counter-procedural mechanics to engage players. In other words, playing an Absurdist video game is only fun when one is not doing things necessary to complete the game. An unintended effect of my class was the distillation of this concept. Allowing additional player progression complicated my student's games exponentially, thanks to the branching paths of adventure games. Students were greatly limited in their ability to complete such complex games, and thus ended up making their games remarkably linear. To make the games more engaging, then, the students were forced to introduce mechanics that did nothing to progress the story and complicate their creation. Unable to achieve 'perfection' in realizing their ambitious projects, my students designed their games around simple, almost anecdotal mechanics - their games were more fun for it. ";s:12:"comment_type";s:0:"";s:14:"comment_parent";s:1:"0";s:7:"user_ID";s:2:"40";s:7:"user_ip";s:12:"69.183.30.68";s:10:"user_agent";s:111:"Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/534.50 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.1 Safari/534.50";s:8:"referrer";s:66:"http://nightmaremode.net/2011/08/elementary-game-development-9892/";s:4:"blog";s:24:"http://nightmaremode.net";s:9:"blog_lang";s:5:"en_US";s:12:"blog_charset";s:5:"UTF-8";s:9:"permalink";s:66:"http://nightmaremode.net/2011/08/elementary-game-development-9892/";s:9:"user_role";s:6:"author";s:21:"akismet_comment_nonce";s:6:"passed";s:12:"POST_comment";s:1258:"Addendum:
